{"author":{"id":"cc8322a500b8739c77faac347808f6026d9ccb7880d0aaa7ad76754163cd7fdb"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782568926,"nonce":"jaE2l6paEyYF/8j2aZeAZeOjpUw=","kind":"spec","title":"Unified entry model — facets over the git DAG (design)"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782568926,"nonce":"ww4bfoE2g3/YA84LMdnA+RtsBBs=","body":"# Unified entry model — facets over the git DAG (design)\n\n**Date:** 2026-06-20\n**Status:** approved (brainstorming → umbrella design, rev. 2 after a daily-use\nwalkthrough; each slice gets its own spec + plan)\n**Scope:** the data model *and* the daily interaction model for a kref entry.\nReframes an entry as one identity carrying independently-mergeable *facets*, so\norganization, provenance, edit-reconciliation, and hygiene each get a home\ninstead of being forced onto the visibility tier. **Umbrella** design: records\nthe coherent model and decomposes it into shippable slices; each slice (§9) gets\nits own spec and plan.\n\n## 1. Context\n\n`kref` stores each entry as a git-bug `entity/dag`: a Lamport-ordered DAG of\noperations under a per-tier ref namespace (`kref-private`/`kref-personal`/\n`kref-shared`). Today's operations are `Create(kind,title)`, `SetTitle`,\n`SetBody`, `SetStatus`, `AddLink`/`RemoveLink`, `Tombstone`/`Restore`. The\ncompiled `Snapshot` exposes id, kind, title, status, tier, body, links, deleted,\ntimestamps, author.\n\nFour needs the current model serves poorly — surfaced, then validated against a\ndaily personal+team walkthrough:\n\n1. **Organization.** `private`/`personal`/`shared` is a *visibility* axis but is\n   the only grouping users reach for, so it gets overloaded. Needs a second,\n   multi-valued axis (labels), orthogonal to who-syncs-it.\n2. **Provenance.** \"Where did this come from?\" — source file/path, originating\n   project, **human vs. agent**. Only author name/email is captured; `add`-ed\n   entries have no path; the source path lives only in the file's\n   `\u003c!-- kref-id --\u003e` trailer (a one-way file→entry pointer).\n3. **Edit reconciliation.** `SetBody` replaces the whole body; the DAG merges by\n   Lamport clock, so concurrent edits don't conflict — sync silently keeps the\n   higher-clock body and shadows the other. (Storage retains both; only the\n   *display* drops one — see §4.1.)\n4. **Lifecycle \u0026 hygiene.** Agents regenerate specs/plans repeatedly, minting\n   near-duplicate and superseded entries. Duplicate titles are the first\n   symptom. Nothing surfaces, groups, or prunes the cruft.\n\nThe walkthrough also exposed missing **content-evolution verbs**: there is no\n`kref update`/`edit`/`status` today — an entry's body or status can only change by\nre-ingesting a file. That makes content evolution foundational, ahead of every\nother facet.\n\n## 2. Product philosophy\n\nThe decisions below cohere around a few principles; state them once so future\nwork doesn't re-litigate them:\n\n- **Write freely, garden periodically.** Capturing and editing never block and\n  never lose data. Cleanup (dedup, supersede, reconcile) is a deliberate,\n  low-friction, *periodic* activity — like `git gc` or inbox-zero — not a\n  per-write tax.\n- **Nothing blocks, nothing is lost, everything is surfaced.** The git model\n  applied to knowledge: divergent versions and duplicates coexist; tooling makes\n  them loud and trivial to resolve.\n- **Malleable until pushed.** Tier membership (and exposure) is fully reversible\n  until `sync push`; after push, content has left the machine and cannot be\n  retracted. `push` is therefore the trust boundary (§5).\n- **One capability core, thin adapters.** All logic lives in `internal/store`;\n  the CLI is an adapter, and a later MCP server is another (§6). No adapter\n  forks behavior; no second source of truth.\n\n## 3. The model: one identity, several facets\n\nAn entry is **one identity (its op-DAG) carrying typed facets, where each facet's\nmerge rule fits its data shape.** Every facet is a family of operations on the\nexisting `entity/dag`, so the entry stays conflict-free-by-construction and\ntravels with the repo. No new storage engine; no second source of truth (§8).\n\n| Facet | Holds | Merge rule | Today |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Content** | title, kind, body (+ evolution verbs) | scalar **LWW** for title/kind; **keep-both + surface** for body | partial; no edit verbs; body clobbers silently |\n| **Classification** | labels/tags | add/remove **set CRDT** | **missing** |\n| **Relations** | typed links | add/remove **set** | exists, unsurfaced |\n| **Lifecycle** | status, deleted (tombstone) | scalar **LWW** / flag | exists; no status verb |\n| **Provenance** | origin events | **append-only log** | mostly missing |\n| **Visibility** | tier | ref namespace (+ `retier`) | exists; no move op |\n\n**The invariant that stops oscillation:** when a new need appears, ask *\"which\nfacet, and what's its merge rule?\"* — set, append-only log, scalar-LWW, or\nkeep-both — rather than overloading the tier. Sets and logs always merge\ncleanly; scalars are last-writer-wins; the one thing that can't auto-merge\n(prose) keeps both versions and surfaces them.\n\n## 4. Facet designs (model level)\n\nEach subsection states operations, `Snapshot` additions, merge rule, and CLI\nsurface. Op encoding, validation, exact flags, and tests belong to the per-slice\nspec.\n\n### 4.1 Content + evolution (slice 1)\n\n**Canonical content surface: markdown where the H1 *is* the title.** `add`,\n`ingest`, `edit`, and `update` all read/write that one shape.\n\n- **`add` derives the title** from the first H1, else the first substantial\n  line; `--title` overrides (reuses `ingest`'s `titleFromMarkdown` spirit).\n  Removes title friction at the front door.\n- **`kref update \u003cid\u003e`** — agent-facing, non-interactive content update: full\n  replace (`--body`/stdin) and/or line-range edits. Emits `SetBody` (and\n  `SetTitle` if the H1 changed). The primitive.\n- **`kref edit \u003cid\u003e`** — human-facing: materialize the entry as `# Title\\n\\nbody`,\n  open `$EDITOR` (fallback `$VISUAL`, then a sane default), write back on save →\n  calls the same update path; title re-derives from the H1.\n- **`kref status \u003cid\u003e \u003cstatus\u003e`** — set lifecycle status (open/active/accepted/\n  superseded). The missing lifecycle verb (T6).\n\n**Body divergence — keep both, surface, never block.** Storage already keeps\nboth: when two machines edit concurrently, `sync pull` creates a merge commit\njoining both branches, so every `SetBody` is retained; only the *display* (LWW)\ndrops one. Because the merge commit descends from both branches, **the next\n`update` naturally resolves the divergence** (its `SetBody` causally dominates\nboth), so divergence is transient and bounded — it cannot pile up.\n\n- **Detect:** an entry is *diverged* when it has concurrent, un-superseded\n  `SetBody` ops (the two sides of a merge commit). The exact `entity/dag` API to\n  enumerate them is a slice investigation; the Lamport clocks needed exist.\n- **Surface (loud, non-blocking):** `⚠ diverged (N versions)` in `ls`/`show`;\n  `kref diff \u003cid\u003e` shows the versions side by side; `--json` carries the flag.\n- **Edit while diverged:** `update`/`edit` proceed but **warn** (\"N\n  unreconciled versions — `kref diff` first\"); the edit then auto-resolves the\n  flag. No refuse, no `--force`.\n- **`kref reconcile \u003cid\u003e`** = sugar: show both versions, drop into an edit\n  pre-seeded with both, save. (No special merge-parent plumbing — the next edit\n  already descends from both.)\n\n**Recall (rides slice 1):** `kref list --search \u003cterm\u003e` — a **linear scan over\ntitles+bodies**, no index, the daily recall workhorse (sub-100ms to thousands of\nentries). The heavyweight ranked/fuzzy/semantic index (bleve) stays deferred\n(§8); `--search` does not depend on it.\n\n### 4.2 Classification — labels (slice 2)\n\n- **Operations:** `AddLabel{label}` / `RemoveLabel{label}`, mirroring\n  `AddLink`/`RemoveLink` and git-bug's `LabelChange` pattern.\n- **Snapshot:** `Labels []string` (sorted set).\n- **Merge:** add/remove **set CRDT** — concurrent label changes always merge.\n- **Free-form** strings; a `prefix:value` convention (`area:auth`, `project:kref`)\n  is encouraged, not enforced — it is what later enables scoping and faceted\n  search without a schema change.\n- **CLI:** `kref add --label area:auth --label spec`; `kref label add|rm \u003cid\u003e\n  \u003clabel\u003e...`; `kref list --label area:auth` (repeatable, AND); labels shown in\n  `show` and compactly in `list`.\n\n### 4.3 Provenance — origin log + path addressing (slice 3)\n\n\u003e **Shipped (slice 3):** `RecordOrigin{actor, actorKind, sourcePath, trigger,\n\u003e time}` with `trigger ∈ {create, ingest}`. **Deferred:** `originRepo` (needs a\n\u003e repo-identity decision) and the `edit`/`retier` triggers (edit lands with the\n\u003e content slice; retier with §4.6, slice 6).\n\n- **Operation:** `RecordOrigin{actor, actorKind, originRepo, sourcePath,\n  trigger}` where `actorKind ∈ {human, agent}`, `trigger ∈ {create, ingest,\n  edit, retier}`. Append-only.\n- **Snapshot:** `Provenance []OriginEvent` (chronological).\n- **Merge:** append-only set — trivially mergeable, and it **resolves the\n  duplicate-by-title question**: one entry may legitimately carry several origin\n  events (ingested from path A on machine X, path B on machine Y) with no\n  overwrite. (Distinct same-title *entries* are a dedup concern — §4.4.)\n- **Population:** `ingest` appends `{trigger: ingest, sourcePath}`; `add`\n  appends `{trigger: create}`; `retier` appends a tier-change event (§4.6).\n  Actor-kind/name comes from `KREF_ACTOR` env or `--actor` (default `human` + git\n  identity); detection mechanism is a slice decision.\n- **Path addressing:** `kref show \u003cpath\u003e` / `kref restore \u003cpath\u003e` detect a path\n  argument, read that file's `\u003c!-- kref-id --\u003e` trailer for the id, resolve it. No\n  schema change; works for `restore` because `rm` only tombstones while the file\n  keeps its trailer; fails cleanly after `purge`.\n\n### 4.4 Hygiene \u0026 consolidation (slice 5)\n\n\"Write freely, garden periodically.\" Two pincers:\n\n- **Default views stay clean even if you never garden.** `list`/`search` hide\n  `superseded` + tombstoned by default, flag `⚠ diverged`, and **collapse exact\n  (normalized) title-duplicate groups** — one row with `(×N)` instead of N rows.\n  `--all` shows everything.\n- **A dedicated review surface — `kref tidy`** (read-only): clusters the likely\n  redundant — duplicate-title groups, diverged entries, superseded chains,\n  (later) stale-by-age — with counts and suggested actions. You then act per\n  cluster.\n\n- **Dedup detection starts cheap:** exact normalized-title collision grouping\n  over the compiled snapshots. Fuzzy/semantic similarity is the bleve/embeddings\n  tier and stays deferred (§8).\n- **Relations surfacing:** `kref links \u003cid\u003e` (incoming/outgoing typed edges);\n  `kref tree \u003cid\u003e` (parent-child, a shallow in-memory walk — no graph engine);\n  `kref supersede \u003cold\u003e \u003cnew\u003e` (sugar: `AddLink supersedes` + set `\u003cold\u003e`\n  superseded). Pure queries over snapshots; no new persistence.\n- **Agent-assistable:** \"merge these N near-duplicates into one canonical and\n  supersede the rest\" is an ideal agent task and a natural later MCP op\n  (`kref_consolidate`, §6).\n\n**Build decisions (resolved for the slice-5 implementation):**\n\n- **No new op types.** The `links` facet already exists (`AddLink`/`RemoveLink`,\n  `OperationType` 5–6; `Snapshot.Links []Link` with `relates | parent-child |\n  supersedes | derived-from`). The only new persistence is a `Store.AddLink`\n  wrapper (mirroring `Store.AddLabel`), used by `supersede`. No `Store.RemoveLink`\n  this slice (nothing consumes it — YAGNI).\n- **Clean-by-default is a human-render concern only.** `store.List` is unchanged,\n  so `list --json` keeps returning the full flat array (existing keys frozen;\n  shell agents unaffected). The human `list` view hides `superseded` (new) on top\n  of the existing hide-`deleted`, and collapses normalized-title duplicate groups\n  to one `(×N)` row (representative = most-recently-updated, tie-break by id). The\n  \"diverged\" flag in the model bullet above is the existing `◆ merged` flag\n  (slice 4, `Snapshot.Merged`) — no new glyph is introduced.\n- **Flag model:** `--all` (new) reveals superseded **and** tombstoned, uncollapsed\n  (sets store `IncludeDelete=true` + disables both human transforms).\n  `--include-deleted` keeps its current narrow meaning (un-hide tombstoned only).\n- **Title normalization is stdlib-only** (`strings.ToLower` → collapse whitespace\n  runs → `TrimSpace`); codepoint-simple, not Unicode-canonical (NFC needs\n  `golang.org/x/text`, a new module slices 1–4 avoided). Punctuation is\n  significant. `entry.NormalizeTitle` is shared by render-collapse and `tidy`.\n  Unicode folding rides along with fuzzy matching into the deferred bleve tier.\n- **`kref tidy`** is a pure read query (`store.Tidy`) with a human view and an\n  additive `--json` shape. Clusters this slice: duplicate-title groups, diverged\n  (`Snapshot.Merged`), superseded chains. Stale-by-age stays deferred.\n- **Relations semantics:** `kref links \u003cid\u003e` = outgoing (`Snapshot.Links`) +\n  incoming (linear scan for links targeting `\u003cid\u003e`). `kref tree \u003cid\u003e` walks\n  `parent-child` over in-memory adjacency, cycle-guarded; convention: a\n  `parent-child` link **from X to Y means Y is X's parent**, so `tree` descends\n  into entries naming `\u003cid\u003e` as parent. `kref supersede \u003cold\u003e \u003cnew\u003e` =\n  `AddLink(new → old, \"supersedes\")` + `SetStatus(old, \"superseded\")`.\n- **Placement:** `tidy`, `links`, `tree` join the **core** group; `supersede`\n  joins **lifecycle** (beside `status`). All route through `emit` and reuse\n  `resolveArg` for id-or-path addressing.\n\n### 4.5 Lifecycle (folded into slices 1 \u0026 5)\n\n`status` (open/active/accepted/superseded) + `deleted` (tombstone) already\nexist. Slice 1 adds the `status` verb; slice 5 uses `superseded` for hygiene.\nTombstone/restore are unchanged, with `restore \u003cpath\u003e` added in slice 3.\n\n### 4.6 Visibility — tier + retier (slice 6b)\n\n- **The id is namespace-independent** (`sha256` of the Create op; tier is the ref\n  namespace, not part of the id). So **retier = move the ref to the new\n  namespace; the id is preserved** — kref-id trailers, links, labels, and\n  provenance all ride along.\n- **Malleable until pushed (§5):** pre-push, promote/demote freely. Post-push,\n  demote-from-`shared` cannot retract what's left the machine; kref detects the\n  pushed state (remote-tracking ref / a per-tier pushed marker) and refuses with\n  an honest warning (\"already pushed to `\u003cremote\u003e` — rotate if sensitive; this\n  only stops future local sync\").\n- **Promote to `shared`** gates exposure: gitleaks rescan (fail-closed),\n  confirmation, and a **warn-and-proceed** on cross-tier dangling links (links to\n  still-private/personal entries teammates won't see).\n- **CLI:** `kref retier \u003cid\u003e \u003ctier\u003e` primitive; `kref share`/`kref promote \u003cid\u003e`\n  sugar; `kref private \u003cid\u003e` panic-button. A `retier` provenance event is recorded.\n- **Caveat:** ops minted under the old tier's **Lamport clock** move into the new\n  tier's clock context — the real slice investigation (id stability is settled).\n\n**Build decisions (resolved for the slice-6b implementation):**\n\n- **Move mechanism = read-append-commit, not CopyRef.** `Store.Retier` reads the\n  entry's ops from the current tier, builds a fresh entity in the target tier\n  (`entry.New(target)` → append every op → append a `retier` provenance op →\n  `Commit`), then `dag.Remove`s the old ref. The op hashes are clock-independent\n  (git-bug deliberately excludes the Lamport clock / parent-op id / depth from\n  the op id — operation.go), so the **id is preserved**; the target tier\n  re-clocks via the normal write path (CopyRef would carry the old namespace's\n  Lamport values and risk git-bug's \"clock jumped too far\" guard). **The Lamport\n  question is resolved this way; Task 1 verifies the round-trip empirically.**\n- **Side effect (documented):** the entity's commit history collapses into one\n  fresh pack in the target tier, so the `◆ merged` flag resets there. All body\n  versions and ops are retained (`kref diff`/`kref log` intact) — only the coarse\n  divergence flag resets.\n- **Atomicity:** commit-into-target then remove-old. A failed remove leaves a\n  recoverable duplicate (same id in two namespaces) that a re-run self-heals; it\n  is reported honestly, never silent.\n- **Promote to shared gate split:** the **rescan is in the core** (`Store.Retier`\n  runs the 6a `scanForPush` fail-closed when promoting to shared — unskippable by\n  any adapter). The **confirmation prompt** (`--yes` to skip) and the\n  **cross-tier dangling-link warning** are CLI-layer UX over store queries\n  (`crossTierLinks`); the core stays non-interactive.\n- **Post-push demote = warn-and-proceed** (not hard-refuse): detected via 6a's\n  pushed-state (`wasPushed`), so `kref private` stays a usable panic button. The\n  warning is honest: it only stops future local sync.\n- **CLI:** `kref promote`/`kref share` are aliases that retier straight to shared;\n  the personal tier is reached via the `retier \u003cid\u003e personal` primitive. All in\n  the lifecycle group, routed through `emit`, id-or-path via `resolveArg`.\n\n## 5. Cross-cutting: `push` is the trust boundary\n\nContent reaches a pushable tier many ways (`add --tier shared`, `update`/`edit`\nadding a secret, `ingest`, promotion). They all funnel through `sync push` before\nleaving the machine. So:\n\n- **Scan-on-push:** `sync push` runs gitleaks on the **delta about to leave**\n  (fail-closed) for any pushable tier, generalizing today's ingest-only scan\n  into a real boundary.\n- **Pushed-state tracking:** a successful push records what left (per-tier\n  marker / remote-tracking ref), which powers the retier rule (§4.6) and the\n  \"what's new since I last pulled\" view (`kref list --new` / `kref log --since-pull`,\n  the T1 capability).\n\nThis is its own slice (6) because retier, scan-on-push, pushed-state, and the\nwhat's-new view share the push-boundary mechanics.\n\n**Build decisions (resolved). Slice 6 is split into two shippable sub-slices,\nand the what's-new view is deferred:**\n\n- **6a — push trust boundary:** scan-on-push + pushed-state. The security gate +\n  foundation. Avoids the Lamport-clock question entirely (it moves no ops between\n  namespaces).\n- **6b — retier:** ref-move (id-preserving), `retier`/`promote`/`share`/`private`,\n  promote gates, provenance event, and the post-push demote refusal — built on\n  6a's pushed-state. Owns the §4.6 Lamport-clock investigation.\n- **What's-new view** (`kref list --new` / `kref log --since-pull`): *resolved as a\n  standalone follow-up.* \"Both directions\" needs two distinct signals — a single\n  marker can't capture incoming, because teammates' content carries older\n  commits/timestamps. So:\n  - **Incoming** (from the last pull): `Store.Pull` is rewritten to drive\n    `dag.MergeAll` directly (same Fetch+merge as `dag.Pull`) and capture the ids\n    it reports `New`/`Updated`, recorded as `kref.incoming.\u003ctier\u003e` (git config,\n    rewritten each pull). This is the only reliable \"from teammates\" signal.\n    `Store.Pull` keeps identical merge behavior (a regression test pins it).\n  - **Unpushed** (local outbound): the existing 6a `pushDelta` (tip ≠ `kref-pushed`).\n  - **`kref list --new`** renders two labeled sections (Incoming, Unpushed),\n    `--json` → `{\"incoming\":[...],\"unpushed\":[...]}`.\n  - **`kref log --since-pull \u003cid\u003e`** = the entry's ops added *after* the last pull\n    (your post-pull edits): at pull, each incoming entry's op-count is recorded\n    (`kref.pulled.\u003cid\u003e`); the log is split there. No pull baseline ⇒ full log + a\n    note. Both commands are new flags on the existing `list`/`log` commands.\n\n**6a build decisions (resolved):**\n\n- **Enforcement lives in `Store.Push`**, not the CLI, so no caller (CLI or future\n  MCP) can bypass the boundary. No new op types and no new CLI command — `kref sync\n  push` transparently gains the gate. The gate applies to every pushable tier\n  (any tier with a remote: personal + shared); private never pushes.\n- **Pushed-state = per-entry local mirror refs.** After a successful push of tier\n  T, each entry's pushed tip is mirrored to `refs/kref-pushed/\u003cnamespace\u003e/\u003cid\u003e`.\n  These are local bookkeeping — `dag.Push` only transfers the tier's own\n  namespace (`kref-\u003ctier\u003e/*`), so `kref-pushed/*` never leaves. Per-entry granularity\n  answers \"was X pushed?\" precisely (the substrate 6b + what's-new consume).\n- **Scan-on-push is delta-based.** For each entry in the tier, compare its current\n  ref tip to its `kref-pushed` mirror: unchanged ⇒ skip (already pushed clean); new\n  or changed ⇒ scan **all its body versions** (the DAG ships full history, so a\n  secret added then edited away still leaves — `BodyVersions` concatenated into\n  one gitleaks run per changed entry; first push of a tier scans everything).\n  Findings ⇒ abort **before any network contact**; clean ⇒ `dag.Push`, then update\n  the mirror refs to the new tips.\n- **Fail-closed, no override.** A finding aborts the tier's push with a precise,\n  secret-free remediation runbook (offending entry id + gitleaks rule; never the\n  secret value; lists all offenders). Because history is immutable, the honest\n  fix is rotate → `kref purge \u003cid\u003e --gc` → recreate clean → re-push (mirrors the\n  existing ingest-block guidance).\n\n## 6. Cross-cutting: interfaces (CLI now, MCP later)\n\n`internal/store` is the only capability core. The CLI (`cmd/kref`) is one thin\nadapter. An **MCP server is a later thin adapter** over the same core — *not* an\nalternative to the CLI and *not* a second source of truth.\n\n- Shell-capable coding agents are already served by the `--json` seam built in\n  the output-UX sweep; MCP earns its keep for **non-shell agent hosts** and for\n  **curated agentic operations** (`kref_recall`, `kref_remember`, `kref_consolidate`)\n  rather than a 1:1 CLI mirror.\n- Build it **after** the facets exist (nothing to expose before then): a `kref mcp`\n  stdio server the host launches per-repo. Deferred slice 7.\n\n**Build decisions (resolved for slice 7):**\n\n- **Dependency:** adopt the official `github.com/modelcontextprotocol/go-sdk`\n  (stable 1.x) — the **first new direct dependency** of the build-out. Rationale:\n  MCP is a real, evolving network protocol with host-compatibility stakes;\n  \"don't reinvent the wheel\" (a maintained, spec-compliant SDK) outweighs the\n  zero-dep streak. `net/rpc/jsonrpc` is JSON-RPC 1.0 (MCP needs 2.0), so stdlib\n  would mean hand-rolling the protocol.\n- **Adapter, not core:** a new `internal/mcpserver` package builds the server and\n  registers tools as **thin handlers over `internal/store`** — mirroring how\n  `cmd/kref`/`render` adapt the same core. The core is unchanged; MCP is a second\n  adapter, never a second source of truth. `cmd/kref` gains a `kref mcp` command\n  (setup group) that runs the server over `mcp.StdioTransport`.\n- **Curated tools (5), not a CLI mirror:** `kref_remember` (Add + labels +\n  agent provenance), `kref_recall` (List/search), `kref_get` (Get), `kref_update`\n  (Update), `kref_supersede` (Supersede). Tool input schemas auto-derive from\n  json-tagged Go param structs (`mcp.AddTool`).\n- **Store lifecycle:** open the store per tool-call (matches the CLI's\n  per-command lifecycle; sidesteps the long-lived-Store concurrency caveat noted\n  in §5). MCP writes are recorded as **agent** provenance.\n- **Testing:** `mcp.NewInMemoryTransports()` connects an in-process client to the\n  server per tool — assert the MCP result and the store side-effect, no stdio\n  subprocess.\n- **Out of scope:** MCP resources/prompts (tools only); the broad\n  link/tree/tidy/retier tools (curated surface, per the bullet above).\n\n## 7. Merge-rule reference\n\n| Data shape | Rule | Facets |\n|---|---|---|\n| Multi-valued membership | add/remove set CRDT | labels, links |\n| Origin history | append-only log | provenance |\n| Single current value | last-writer-wins (Lamport) | title, kind, status, deleted |\n| Prose (no clean auto-merge) | keep both → detect → surface → resolve on next edit | body |\n\n## 8. Index / storage (decided: defer; no graph DB)\n\nThe query layer is **derived, deferrable, and reversible**, so it is *not*\ncoupled to this model. Today: compile-on-read + linear filter/scan in Go —\nadequate to low-thousands of entries, zero new dependencies, and enough for\n`--search` (§4.1) and exact-title dedup (§4.4). If/when scale demands a\npersistent index, the choice is **SQLite as a disposable materialized view**\n(pure-Go `modernc.org/sqlite`; FTS5 for ranked search; recursive CTEs for the\nshallow link traversal), rebuilt from the refs — never a second authority. An\nembedded **graph DB is rejected**: only one of six facets is graph-shaped and kref\nlink structure is shallow, while the Go embedded-graph ecosystem is weak\n(`cayley` semi-dormant; `kùzu`/embedded-Neo4j drag in cgo/JVM). This section\nrecords the decision; it ships no code.\n\n## 9. Decomposition and build order\n\n\u003e **Status: all shipped (merged to `main`).** Slices 1–5 shipped as planned;\n\u003e slice 6 split into **6a** (push trust boundary: scan-on-push + pushed-state)\n\u003e and **6b** (retier), with the **what's-new view** (`list --new` /\n\u003e `log --since-pull`) shipped as a standalone follow-up; slice 7 (MCP) shipped\n\u003e last, adding the first external dependency (`modelcontextprotocol/go-sdk`).\n\nDependency- and value-ordered. Each slice is independently shippable and gets its\nown spec → plan → implementation; JSON shapes stay additive (new fields only,\nexisting keys frozen); each extends `internal/render` and the `--json` seam.\n\n1. **Content evolution + recall** (§4.1) — `add` title-derivation, `update`,\n   `edit`, `status`, `kref list --search`. Foundational: makes the KB usable\n   (capture → recall → edit) and is a prerequisite for divergence (slice 4).\n2. **Labels** (§4.2) — classification; unblocks scoping and tidy.\n3. **Provenance + path addressing** (§4.3) — answers the founding path/duplicate\n   questions; `show`/`restore` by path; human-vs-agent attribution.\n4. **Body divergence** (§4.1) — keep-both detection, `diff`, `⚠`, `reconcile`,\n   warn-on-edit. Depends on slice 1.\n5. **Hygiene \u0026 consolidation** (§4.4) — clean-by-default views, dup collapse,\n   `kref tidy`, `supersede`, `links`/`tree`. Depends on labels (2) + status (1) +\n   divergence (4).\n6. **Retier + push trust boundary** (§4.6, §5) — `retier`/`share`/`private`,\n   scan-on-push, pushed-state tracking, `--new`/`--since-pull`. Security-grouped.\n7. **MCP adapter** (§6) — thin curated agent endpoint. After the facets exist.\n\nScan-on-push (slice 6) may be pulled forward if active team sharing lands sooner;\nthe existing ingest scan covers the main ingress until then.\n\n## 10. Non-goals\n\n- **No graph database / no second store** (§8).\n- **No vector embeddings / semantic retrieval / GraphRAG** — that is an\n  agent-knowledge-graph product; this is *linked notes*.\n- **No search index now** — `bleve` is transitive only; `--search` is a linear\n  scan. The index is deferred until a scan is measurably slow.\n- **No fuzzy/semantic dedup now** — exact title-collision only (§4.4).\n- **No CRDT-text body / no auto 3-way conflict markers** — keep-both + surface\n  (§4.1).\n- **No materialize-to-files (`kref checkout` / `.kref/`)** — remains deferred.\n- **No staleness/TTL** yet — a future provenance-style `last-verified` stamp that\n  feeds `kref tidy`.\n\n## 11. Open questions (resolved per slice, recorded here)\n\n- **Content (1):** `update` line-range edit format (line numbers are brittle as\n  content shifts — full-replace is the reliable primitive; line-range is a\n  convenience). `edit` default editor fallback chain.\n- **Divergence (4):** the precise `entity/dag` API to enumerate concurrent\n  un-superseded `SetBody` ops.\n- **Provenance (3):** actor-kind source (`--actor` vs `KREF_ACTOR` vs both) and the\n  default human identity record.\n- **Hygiene (5):** *resolved.* Title normalization = stdlib lowercase + collapse\n  whitespace + trim (punctuation significant; NFC/fuzzy deferred to the bleve\n  tier). No write-time nudge — writes stay non-blocking; duplicates surface lazily\n  in `list` collapse and `kref tidy`. Clean-by-default is human-render only\n  (`list --json` unchanged); `--all` reveals everything (see §4.4 build decisions).\n- **Retier / push (6):** *partially resolved.* Slice **6a** resolves\n  pushed-state (per-entry local mirror refs `refs/kref-pushed/\u003cns\u003e/\u003cid\u003e`, a\n  kref-maintained marker — not git-bug remote-tracking refs) and scan-on-push delta\n  computation (skip entries whose tip equals their mirror; scan all body versions\n  of changed entries; fail-closed in `Store.Push`). Slice **6b** *resolves* the\n  ref-move: read-append-commit re-clocks the entity into the target namespace via\n  the normal write path (CopyRef rejected — it would carry foreign Lamport\n  values); the id is preserved because op hashes exclude the clock. See §4.6\n  build decisions.\n- **MCP (7):** the curated tool surface (recall/remember/consolidate/get/update/\n  list/link) and whether entries are also exposed as MCP resources."}]}